article.description:
Jason Kidd returned from a one-game absence to
post a triple-double with 13 points, 11 rebounds and 10 assists, leading the New Jersey Nets to a 93=70 victory at Seattle.
article.headline: Kidd, K-Mart serve 1-2 punch
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- Byron Scott saw plenty of Alonzo Mourning in the way the New Jersey Nets played in their first game without the veteran center. Jason Kidd returned from a one-game absence to post a triple-double with 13 points, 11 rebounds and 10 assists, leading New Jersey to a 93-70 victory over the Seattle SuperSonics on Tuesday night. Kenyon Martin had season highs with 27 points and 14 rebounds as the Nets opened a five-game Western road trip one day after learning Mourning was retiring because his life-threatening kidney illness had worsened. "There was a lot of 'Zo," Scott said. "This team has had very great character and resiliency the last couple of seasons, and that's Alonzo Mourning to a T. That's what he's been about his whole career." Seattle's 25 points in the second half broke the previous franchise record for fewest points in a half -- 26 set last Nov. 29 against Houston. "There was no execution," said Vladimir Radmanovic, who scored 10 points on 4-of-16 shooting. "Eleven points in the fourth quarter, 14 in the third. That's not our game. We can't beat anybody like that." Richard Jefferson added 18 points and Kerry Kittles scored 11 for New Jersey, which ended a two-game losing streak and had won only three times in nine games. Rashard Lewis led Seattle with 14 points but the Sonics shot only 33 percent (23-of-68). Calvin Booth and Brent Barry each had 12, while Ronald Murray, who was averaging 23.9 points, was held to 11. The Nets put the victory away with an 17-3 run in the fourth quarter. Fans booed after Kidd, who sat out Saturday's loss to Toronto because of a sore left knee, scored an easy layup with 4:42 remaining off Seattle's 13th turnover. "There's a lot going on with this team with the loss of 'Zo, with the way we've been playing the last 12 games," Kidd said. "Right now, it's just a matter of us trying to refocus on doing the things we've done in the past." That meant establishing a fullcourt game and getting easy baskets. "We got some stops in the second half, then we got our running game going," Martin said. The Sonics finished with 15 turnovers, leading to 22 points for New Jersey. It was Seattle's fourth loss in its last five home games, and the Sonics barely held on Sunday to beat Washington after blowing an 18-point second-half lead. "It was just the same thing again," coach Nate McMillan said. "It starts with turnovers and then it just continues to tailspin." Before tipoff, Scott expressed concern that Mourning's retirement might impact his team's play. His concerns seemed warranted when the Nets missed 10 straight baskets over one stretch of the first and second quarters. New Jersey regrouped after halftime, erasing Seattle's 45-36 lead at the break by scoring the first 13 points of the third quarter. The Nets looked lost early, shooting 4-of-22 in the second quarter and missing 10 straight when their last two shots of the first quarter were added. The Sonics closed the first half with a 6-2 burst to lead 45-36 at the break. "We stuck with it," Kidd said. "That's just the character of this team. We're not going to roll over and die. It's too early in the season. We came out and made some shots, got some stops defensively." Three-pointers by Radmanovic and Brent Barry after New Jersey's 13-0 run kept the Sonics close, but Seattle trailed 64-59 going into the final quarter after shooting 5-of-19 and being outscored 28-14 in the third.

Game notes
The Nets activated G Lucious Harris, on the injured list since Oct. 27 with lower back pain, to fill Mourning's roster spot. Harris scored three points on 1-of-5 shooting. ... Sonics rookie C-F Nick Collison, out for the season after shoulder surgery, had his Kansas jersey retired in a ceremony in Lawrence, Kan. ... An MRI test showed no injury to Radmanovic's left knee. He missed practice Monday. ... Kidd said the rest helped his knee. "It feels great," he said.
